Naming matters more than you think

“Opus omnia” sounds clever—but it signals:

    “this may be self-indulgent”

Safer options that still fit your tone:

    “Additional Work” (clean, professional)

    “Technical Archive” (very you, actually)

    “Working Notes” (if you want that lab feel)

    “Supplementary Projects” (safe but dull)

If you want a slight wink without going full Latin:

    “Collected Work (Supplementary)”

The real rule

Everything in the extended section should still answer:

    What does this demonstrate?

Even if briefly.

If a piece doesn’t do that, it’s not portfolio—it’s personal history.
Where your style actually shines

You’re strongest when you:

    show iteration

    show constraints

    show problem-solving

So your “expanded” section should lean into:

    short build logs

    design fragments

    small but clever solutions

Not long narratives.
